      "solution": "#include <unistd.h>\n#include <stdio.h>\n\nvoid\tputnbr_base_rec(long n, char *base, int base_len)\n{\n\tif (n >= base_len)\n\t\tputnbr_base_rec(n / base_len, base, base_len);\n\tprintf(\"%c\", base[n % base_len]);\n}\n\nvoid\tputnbr_base(int nbr, char *base)\n{\n\tlong\tn;\n\tint\t\tbase_len;\n\n\tbase_len = 0;\n\twhile (base[base_len])\n\t\tbase_len++;\n\n\tn = nbr;\n\n\tif (n < 0)\n\t{\n\t\tprintf(\"%c\", '-');\n\t\tn = -n;\n\t}\n\n\tputnbr_base_rec(n, base, base_len);\n}\n\nint\tmain(void)\n{\n\tint\t\tnb;\n\tchar\tbase[100] = \"\";\n\n\tscanf(\"%d\", &nb);\n\tscanf(\" %99[^\\n]\", base);\n\n\tputnbr_base(nb, base);\n\tprintf(\"\\n\");\n\n\treturn (0);\n}\n",
      "statement": "Convert a base-10 integer into the given base.\n\nThe base is represented by a string of unique characters.\n\nExamples:\n- \"01\" -> base 2\n- \"0123456789\" -> base 10\n- \"0123456789abcdef\" -> base 16",
